Rahoton U.N. ya ce fiye da 6,000 'yan ta'adda na Pakistan suna ɓoye a Afghanistan, mafi yawan suna daga ƙungiyar ta'addanci ta Pakistan da aka haramta da take da alhakin yin matafiyar sojoji da jama'a na Pakistan.
Rahoton da aka saki wannan mako ya ce rukunin, wanda aka sani da Tehreek-e-Taliban (TTP), ya haɗa da ƙungiyar ƙasashen Afagan da ke ƙungiyar ƙasashen Musulunci.
Wasu daga cikin ƙungiyar TTP sun haɗu da ƙungiyar IS wadda take da ƙungiyar ta a Arewacin Afghanistan.
Gwamnatin Afagan ba ta amsa kiran da Associated Press ta yi a ranar Lahadi ba don bayani.
Rahoton ya ce IS a Afaganistan, wanda aka sani da IS a yankin Khorasan, ya samu rauni mai tsanani daga kungiyoyin tsaro na Afaganistan da kuma kungiyoyin Amurka da NATO, har ma da lokutan da kungiyar Taliban ta Afaganistan.
Rahoton ya shirya ta ƙungiyar binciken U.N. da kuma taɗakarar hana yin laifi, wadda take bincika ƙungiyoyin ta'addanci a duniya.
Rahoton ya yi kiyasin cewa jama'ar IS a Afaganistan ya kai 2,200, kuma yayin da shugabancinsu ya yi ƙasa, IS har yanzu ya ƙunshi cikin shugabanninsa wani ƙasar Siriya mai suna Abu Said Mohammad al-Khorasani.
Rahoton ya ce kuma jami'an binciken sun samu labarin cewa biyu daga cikin masu ruwa da tsaki na ƙungiyar Islama, Abu Qutaibah da Abu Hajar al-Iraqi, sun zo ƙasar Afaganistan daga Tsakiyar Turai.
K despite ɗaukar ƙasa a yankin, (Ƙasar Musulunci) ta ci gaba da iya aikata makamai masu yawa a cikin sassan ƙasar, ciki har da Kabul.
